;; Kernel-enforced isolation for the untrusted builder (macOS seatbelt).
;;
;; Three prior containment attempts failed because every seal lived inside the
;; blast radius it was trying to contain: a cwd sandbox (escaped via
;; xcodebuildmcp scheme resolution), disabling that MCP (escaped via an
;; absolute-path file edit), and `chmod -R a-w` on the real repo — which the
;; builder defeated by running `chmod u+w` on the file. File modes are
;; advisory against an agent that can run chmod; a seatbelt profile is not.
;; Here the kernel denies the syscall regardless of ownership or mode, so
;; chmod buys the builder nothing.
;;
;; Scope note: only the REAL Aria repo is walled off — not the whole
;; workspace — because arm B/C tooling (verify.sh) must still read the venv
;; Python and the local VLM under tools/llmops. The builder's own sandbox
;; copy, its DerivedData, and all cell output live under /private/tmp and
;; stay fully writable.
;;
;; Usage: sandbox-exec -f builder.sb <builder command>
;; Verify with: sandbox-exec -f builder.sb bash -c 'ls <real repo>'  -> denied

(version 1)
(allow default)

;; Metadata reads stay ALLOWED, file CONTENTS and all writes are denied.
;;
;; A blanket `file-read*` deny is too blunt: opencode stats the real repo at
;; startup (project/session registry) and dies with
;;   EPERM: operation not permitted, lstat '.../Aria_Music_Browser'
;; before the builder model ever runs. Denying only `file-read-data` lets that
;; lstat succeed while still hiding source contents, so the builder cannot
;; "diagnose" against pristine code it was never meant to see — round 1's
;; contamination produced confident, wrong conclusions exactly that way.
;;
;; `file-write*` is the load-bearing denial: it is what makes `chmod u+w`
;; useless and keeps the operator's repo safe.
(deny file-read-data file-write*
      (subpath "/Users/chait/MusicAppIOS/Aria_Music_Browser"))
